div.h1: Physical Allocator Comparison: Bitmap vs Buddy System

g.text: Why Linux Migrated Bitmap to Buddy

div.p: Each 64B cache line = 512 bits = 512 frames = 2MB RAM

g.text: Allocate: O(n) scan - worst case 32768 reads
Free: O(1) - clear one bit, done
Contiguous N frames: O(n) scan for N consecutive 0-bits
Double-free detect: O(1) - test bit before clear

div.p: Scan starts from last successful allocation
Hot path: same cache line holds 512 adjacent frames
After warm-up: 128KB bitmap stays resident in L2 cache

g.text: O(n) allocation slow for large bitmaps
Linux migrated away due to fragmentation at scale
Allocate: O(log n) - find order, pop from free list
Free: O(log n) - coalesce buddies up the tree
Contiguous N frames: O(1) - pop from correct order
External fragmentation: ZERO for power-of-2 sizes

text.tspan: Split Order-3 Left into two Order-2 blocks

g.text: Order-2 Right in free list? YES -> merge to Order-3
Order-3 buddy (0x108000) free? YES -> merge to Order-4
Result: full 64KB block restored. Zero fragmentation.
O(log n) alloc and free - fast at scale
Powers Linux alloc_pages() and 2MB/1GB huge pages
Free list per order = cache-friendly for common sizes
Metadata: bitmap PLUS free list pointers per order
Complex to implement correctly: ~500 lines of C
Overkill for small systems under 64MB RAM
Bitmap: free frames scattered across address space
2MB request (huge page, DMA buffer, GPU memory)
Must scan 128KB bitmap for 512 contiguous frames
FAILS even with 1GB free RAM if no contiguous run exists
Every free block of size 2^k is aligned to 2^k pages
2MB request (order-9): O(1) pop from order-9 list
Coalescing on free restores higher-order blocks automatically
No fragmentation possible for power-of-2 aligned requests
kmem_cache_alloc() - SLUB slab allocator above buddy for typed objects
kmalloc() - SLUB size-class slabs for variable kernel allocations
vmalloc() - virtual contiguous but physically scattered (large)
Simple and correct: ~100 lines of C
Use search_hint for amortized O(1) sequential allocs
128KB metadata fits in L2 cache after warm-up
Sufficient for learning OS with small RAM and few processes
Required for huge pages and DMA contiguous alloc
Add SLUB slab allocator above buddy for typed kernel objects
Necessary for systems over 1GB RAM and production workloads
